    {
      "op_id": "OP-079",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_dimensions",
      "record": {
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "relational_environment": 1,
        "relational_environment_note": "All four rings active. Ring 1 dominates. Ring 2 substantially present (God remembers, searches minds, renews the nous, writes law on dianoia, gives mind of Christ). Ring 3 present through shared-mind vocabulary, remembrance in prayer, conscience in community. Ring 4 marginal through noēma (Satan's designs on the mind).",
        "spirit_soul_body": 1,
        "spirit_soul_body_note": "Mind operates primarily at soul-level. Spirit-mind distinction explicit in 1 Cor 14:14-15 (nous vs pneuma in prayer). Body appears as instrument and marker of mind-states. Somatic-attention connection implicit throughout sha.mar corpus.",
        "inner_operations": 1,
        "inner_operations_note": "Full range documented: remembering and forgetting; planning and devising; inclining and orienting; evaluating from within (conscience); changing (metanoeō, na.cham); collapsing into madness or maintaining sobriety; attending deliberately. Renewal of the mind (Rom 12:2) is the most distinctive inner operation.",
        "being": 1,
        "being_note": "Ye.tser (formed inclination) is the primary dispositional Hebrew term. Sōfrōn family documents formed character of sound-mindedness. Froneō operates as characterising disposition in Phil 2:5. Mind of Christ (1 Cor 2:16) is the supreme example of transferred orientation of being.",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "Dimensional profile for registry 112 — all four dimensions active"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-080",
      "operation": "update_registry",
      "registry_no": 112,
      "set": {
        "sb_classification": "confirmed_characteristic",
        "sb_classification_reasoning": null,
        "carry_forward": 1
      },
      "description": "Inner being standing: confirmed_characteristic. Carry forward: true."
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-081",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F001",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "term_behaviour",
        "finding": "Memory in biblical vocabulary is an active, covenantal, morally significant act — not passive cognitive retrieval. God's remembering produces redemptive action; Israel's commanded remembering constitutes covenant identity; forgetting is moral defection.",
        "anchor_verses": "Gen 8:1, Exo 2:24, Deu 5:15, Deu 8:2, Joh 14:26",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F001 — term_behaviour"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-082",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F002",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "theological_note",
        "finding": "The mind is a moral organ before it is an intellectual one. It can be debased, blinded, corrupted, renewed, and transferred (mind of Christ). Romans 12:2 presents renewal of the nous as the locus of personal transformation.",
        "anchor_verses": "Rom 1:28, Rom 12:2, Eph 4:17, Col 1:21, 1Cor 2:16",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F002 — theological_note"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-083",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F003",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "etymology",
        "finding": "The ye.tser (formed inclination) is the OT anthropology's closest approach to a foundational moral disposition. Gen 6:5 and 8:21 establish it as bent toward evil from youth — the dispositional substrate generating particular thoughts and plans.",
        "anchor_verses": "Gen 6:5, Gen 8:21, Isa 26:3",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F003 — etymology"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-084",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F004",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "verse_pattern",
        "finding": "The cha.shav root documents that the same mental faculty produces artistic design, moral reasoning, and malicious plotting — there is no separate creative vs rational faculty in Hebrew anthropology. God's planning uses the same root as wicked scheming.",
        "anchor_verses": "Pro 12:5, Pro 15:26, Jer 29:11, Ps 140:2",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F004 — verse_pattern"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-085",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F005",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "theological_note",
        "finding": "Fronēma (the set mindset) in Romans 8:5-7 is the determinative factor for life or death, peace or enmity with God — making the mind's fundamental orientation soteriologically significant, not merely morally relevant.",
        "anchor_verses": "Rom 8:5, Rom 8:6, Rom 8:7",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F005 — theological_note"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-086",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F006",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "theological_note",
        "finding": "Suneidēsis (conscience) is the NT's distinctive contribution with no direct Hebrew equivalent. The conscience can be weak, clear, seared, or purified (Heb 9:14), and functions as a bridge between inner life and relational/covenantal domains.",
        "anchor_verses": "Rom 2:15, 1Cor 8:7, Heb 9:14, 1Tim 4:2",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F006 — theological_note"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-087",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F007",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "verse_pattern",
        "finding": "Deu 4:9 functionally links the sha.mar attentiveness cluster with the za.khar memory cluster: vigilant attentiveness is the means by which memory is maintained; forgetting is the product of failed attentiveness.",
        "anchor_verses": "Deu 4:9",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F007 — verse_pattern"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-088",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F008",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "term_behaviour",
        "finding": "The 1 Cor 14:14-15 nous/pneuma distinction is the sharpest NT terminological boundary between mind-level and spirit-level inner operation — directly relevant to the Framework B spirit-soul-body boundary investigation.",
        "anchor_verses": "1Cor 14:14, 1Cor 14:15",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F008 — term_behaviour"
    },
    {
      "op_id": "OP-089",
      "operation": "insert",
      "table": "wa_session_b_findings",
      "record": {
        "finding_id": "112-F009",
        "registry_id": 112,
        "file_id": 148,
        "finding_type": "verse_pattern",
        "finding": "Double-mindedness (dipsuchos/se.eph) documents inner division as a cross-testament pathology. James presents inner unity as a condition for receiving from God and for effective action; Ps 119:113 makes it a moral stance.",
        "anchor_verses": "Jas 1:8, Jas 4:8, Psa 119:113",
        "raised_date": "2026-03-27",
        "session_b_instruction": "WA-SessionB-Extraction-Instruction-v5.1"
      },
      "description": "112-F009 — verse_pattern"
    },
    {
